<Base title="Kraft Heinz / MiO — Case Study">

  <div class="section">
    <a class="breadcrumb" href="/Personal/case-studies/">← <span>Case Studies</span> / Kraft Heinz / MiO</a>
    <div class="cs-hero" style="border:0;padding:0;overflow:hidden"><img src="/Personal/Images/MiO/mio-cs-gfx-1.jpg" alt="MiO digital shelf case study graphic" style="width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;display:block" /></div>
    <div class="cs-tags"><span class="cs-tag">CPG</span><span class="cs-tag">eCommerce</span><span class="cs-tag">Creative Direction</span><span class="cs-tag">Enterprise</span></div>
    <div class="cs-title">Rebuilding MiO's digital shelf into a conversion system</div>
    <div class="cs-subtitle">Led the digital shelf transformation for MiO — rebuilding UX and multi-channel creative into a unified conversion system that contributed to measurable Amazon sales lift.</div>
    <div class="cs-meta-card">
      <div class="cs-meta-row"><div class="cs-meta-label">Client</div><div class="cs-meta-value">Kraft Heinz via Imaginary Content</div></div>
      <div class="cs-meta-row"><div class="cs-meta-label">Duration</div><div class="cs-meta-value">Feb 2020 – Oct 2021</div></div>
      <div class="cs-meta-row"><div class="cs-meta-label">Role</div><div class="cs-meta-value">Art Director</div></div>
      <div class="cs-meta-row"><div class="cs-meta-label">Industry</div><div class="cs-meta-value">CPG / Enterprise eCommerce</div></div>
      <div class="cs-meta-row"><div class="cs-meta-label">Lead Brand</div><div class="cs-meta-value">MiO</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="section">
    <div class="stat-strip" style="grid-template-columns:repeat(4,minmax(0,1fr))">
      <div class="stat-box"><div class="stat-num">~8%</div><div class="stat-label">Amazon sales lift, MiO YoY</div></div>
      <div class="stat-box"><div class="stat-num">$143K</div><div class="stat-label">Brand Store sales generated</div></div>
      <div class="stat-box"><div class="stat-num">374</div><div class="stat-label">Digital assets produced for MiO</div></div>
      <div class="stat-box"><div class="stat-num">39</div><div class="stat-label">SKUs supported</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-label">Context · Action · Result</div>
    <div class="car-grid">
      <div class="car-sidebar">
        <div class="car-step active" onclick="switchCar(this,'car-kh-1')"><div class="car-step-label">01 · Context</div><div class="car-step-title">The situation</div></div>
        <div class="car-step" onclick="switchCar(this,'car-kh-2')"><div class="car-step-label">02 · Action</div><div class="car-step-title">What I did</div></div>
        <div class="car-step" onclick="switchCar(this,'car-kh-3')"><div class="car-step-label">03 · Result</div><div class="car-step-title">What it produced</div></div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div id="car-kh-1" class="car-content">
          <div class="car-content-label">01 · Context</div>
          <div class="car-content-title">Strong brand. Fragmented shelf.</div>
          <div class="car-content-body">MiO had strong brand recognition and a loyal customer base, but its digital shelf presence wasn't converting as well as it should have. The Amazon Brand Store was outdated. A+ content lacked structure. Kroger and retail media placements were inconsistent. Programmatic and retailer creative were being adapted channel by channel without a unified conversion logic.<br /><br />This was not just a design issue. It was revenue leakage.<br /><br />The shelf was not structured to help customers make decisions — which directly impacted conversion.<br /><br />Brand, retail, and media teams were producing assets independently, which created a fragmented shopping experience across Amazon, Kroger, and paid media. MiO looked different depending on where shoppers encountered it, and the experience was not structured around how people scan, compare, and decide online.<br /><br />The redesign was grounded in Kraft Heinz's eCommerce shopper insights and consumer decision tree data — not assumptions. Flavor, sugar claims, and nutrition callouts were the top purchase drivers for online beverage enhancer buyers, and the existing shelf content was not structured around any of them. MiO's target consumer — the 'Pleasure Hacker,' a 35-year-old who wants bold flavor without the guilt — was not being served by a shelf that failed to communicate zero sugar, zero calories, and flavor variety within the first scroll.<br /><br />MiO became the flagship project where I owned the digital shelf transformation end-to-end and where the work was tied to concrete performance metrics.</div>
        </div>
        <div id="car-kh-2" class="car-content" style="display:none">
          <div class="car-content-label">02 · Action</div>
          <div class="car-content-title">Rebuilt the shelf as a system, not a set of assets.</div>
          <div class="car-content-body">The goal was to turn fragmented creative into a unified system that guided users from discovery to purchase — structured around the way MiO shoppers actually make decisions.<br /><br /><strong>A. Amazon A+ Content Redesign</strong> — Rebuilt MiO's A+ content as a conversion system mapped directly to the consumer decision tree. The top purchase drivers for online beverage enhancer buyers were flavor (ranked #1), price (#2), brand (#3), sugar claims (#4), and nutrition callouts (#5). The redesign introduced a content hierarchy that addressed each of these in order: value proposition above the fold, a competitive comparison module showing MiO at 0g sugar and 0 calories against juice (20g/200cal), soda (50g/120cal), and energy drinks (61g/240cal), product line breakdowns across Original, Energy, Vitamins, and Sport, and FAQ content sourced from real Amazon Q&amp;A and review data to reduce purchase friction. Every module was designed for scan behavior, product differentiation, and decision-making inside Amazon's constraints.<br /><br /><strong>B. Amazon Brand Store</strong> — Designed the full MiO Brand Store experience across desktop and mobile. Built the hero banner system, product grid with lifestyle and product image rhythm, sub-brand navigation across Original, Energy, Vitamins, and Sport categories, and category CTAs driving shoppers into product pages. The Brand Store was structured as a discovery-to-purchase funnel — not a brand gallery. The store generated $143,620 in sales from 108,287 visitors during the tracking period, with 10,608 orders and an average of 2.72 units per order. The Original sub-brand page drove the highest revenue at $48,939.<br /><br /><strong>C. Multi-Channel Creative System</strong> — Created a scalable MiO creative system across Kroger banners, Amazon merch banners, programmatic display, carousel images, and SKU-level hero assets across all 39 SKUs (28 unique flavors, 8 additional sizes, 3 variety packs). 374 assets total. The carousel strategy was mapped per sub-brand with a specific content sequence: mobile-ready hero image, 'We Fix Water' brand moment with flume photography, customizable use-case imagery, competitive comparison chart, flavor portfolio shot, servings and size callout, sub-brand positioning message, and verified purchaser review. The system translated MiO's visual language — ink-in-water photography, product lineup compositions, and 'We Fix Water' / 'Bold Flavor' messaging — across every channel's specs without losing consistency. Each SKU required consistent positioning while adapting to format, size, and channel constraints — without breaking the overall system.<br /><br /><strong>D. Video and Motion</strong> — Storyboarded and built graphics for MiO animated product video content used in A+ environments. The video work translated the product use case visually for a scroll-heavy shopping environment where shoppers make fast decisions.<br /><br /><strong>E. Team and Execution</strong> — Directed a production designer and junior designer on the MiO account in a matrix structure. The channel mix was almost entirely digital: eCommerce, programmatic, retail media, and social. This required maintaining brand consistency, UX clarity, and performance alignment across high-volume asset production without letting quality degrade.</div>
        </div>
        <div id="car-kh-3" class="car-content" style="display:none">
          <div class="car-content-label">03 · Result</div>
          <div class="car-content-title">Measurable lift, honest attribution.</div>
          <div class="car-content-body">The MiO digital shelf redesign contributed to a ~8% Amazon sales lift, year-over-year. The lift occurred during the digital shelf redesign window I led across A+ content, Amazon Brand Store, retailer pages, programmatic creative, and multi-channel assets. The result was reported through Kraft Heinz internal analytics.<br /><br />The MiO Brand Store I designed generated $143,620 in sales from 108,287 visitors, producing 10,608 orders at an average of 2.72 units per order. The Original sub-brand page drove the highest revenue at $48,939, followed by Energy at $21,585 and Sport at $17,394. Amazon Sponsored Brands drove 27,398 visits and $84,406 in sales. Organic traffic contributed 15,868 visits and $42,491 in sales.<br /><br />374 digital assets were produced for MiO across 39 SKUs spanning eCommerce, programmatic, and retail channels. Full Amazon Brand Store shipped across desktop and mobile. Kroger banners covered 6+ size variants. The animated product video I storyboarded shipped as A+ content.<br /><br />More importantly, the work established a repeatable system for how MiO showed up across channels — replacing fragmented execution with a consistent conversion framework grounded in real shopper data.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-label">Key insight</div>
    <div class="foundation-card">
      <div class="foundation-section-title">Most teams treat the digital shelf as production. The teams that convert treat it as a system.</div>
      <div class="foundation-desc">The ~8% lift did not come from making MiO look better. It came from aligning shopper decision data, brand storytelling, conversion UX, and retail platform constraints into one operating system.</div>
      <div class="foundation-desc">MiO's consumer decision tree showed that flavor, sugar claims, and nutrition callouts were the top purchase drivers — but the shelf was not structured around any of them. The redesign fixed that alignment.</div>
      <div class="foundation-desc" style="margin-bottom:0">From the Brand Store down to the last Kroger sidebar banner, every asset was built to guide a specific shopper through a specific decision in a specific channel. That is what turned the shelf from a collection of deliverables into a revenue system.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

